Claims CLAIMS I claim: 1. An apparatus for supporting a person's head while the person is seated, the apparatus comprising: a sling having a first end, a second end, a distal surface, and a proximal surface opposite the distal surface; a first spring driven reel operably associated with the first end of the sling; a second spring driven reel operably associated with the second end of the sling; a first sling strap having a proximal end and a distal end, the proximal end of the first sling strap terminating in the first spring driven reel operably associated with the first end of the sling and the distal end of the first sling strap having a first coupler; a second sling strap having a proximal end and a distal end, the proximal end of the second sling strap terminating in the second spring driven reel operably associated with the second end of the sling and the distal end of the second sling strap having a second coupler; and, a seat having a seat back, the seat back having a back side, a top, and a front side, and the seat back having a first complementary coupler complementary to the first coupler on the distal end of the first sling strap and located proximal to the top of the seat back, and the seat back having a second complementary coupler complementary to the second coupler on the distal end of the second sling strap and located proximal to the top of the seat back. 2. The apparatus of Claim 1, wherein; 

the first coupler, the first complementary coupler, the second coupler, and the second complementary coupler are magnetic. 3. The apparatus of Claim 1, wherein; the first coupler and the first complementary coupler are complementary portions of a first snapping coupler, and the second coupler and the second complementary coupler are complementary portions of a second snapping coupler. 4. The apparatus of Claim 1, wherein; the first spring driven reel locks to fix the length of the first sling strap that extends from the first spring driven reel, and the second spring driven reel locks to fix the length of the second sling strap that extends from the second spring driven reel. 5. An apparatus for supporting a person's head while the person is seated, the apparatus comprising: a sling having a first end, a second end, a distal surface, and a proximal surface opposite the distal surface; a first spring driven reel operably associated with the first end of the sling; a second spring driven reel operably associated with the second end of the sling; a sling strap having a first end and a second end, the first end of the sling strap terminating in the first spring driven reel operably associated with the first end of the sling and the second end of the sling strap terminating in the second spring driven reel operably associated with the second end of the sling; 

a first coupler attached to the sling strap in between the first spring driven reel and the second spring driven reel; and, a seat having a seat back, the seat back having a back side, a top, and a front side, and the seat back having a first complementary coupler complementary to the first coupler attached to the sling strap and located proximal to the top of the seat back. 6. The apparatus of Claim 5, wherein; the first coupler and the first complementary coupler are magnetic. 7. The apparatus of Claim 5, further comprising: a second coupler attached to the sling strap in between the first spring driven reel and the second spring driven reel; and, a second complementary coupler on the seat back, the second complementary coupler being proximal to the top of the seat back and complementary to the second coupler on the sling strap. 8. The apparatus of Claim 7, wherein; the second coupler and the second complementary coupler are magnetic. 9. The apparatus of Claim 5, wherein; the first spring driven reel locks to fix the length of the sling strap that is retained within the first spring driven reel, and the second spring driven reel locks to fix the length of the sling strap that is retained within the second spring driven reel. 10. An apparatus for supporting a person's head while the person is seated, the apparatus comprising: a spring driven reel; a first strap having a proximal end and a distal end, the proximal end of the first strap terminating in the spring driven reel and the distal end of the first strap having a first coupler; a second strap having a proximal end and a distal end, the proximal end of the second strap being fixed externally to the spring driven reel and the distal end of the second strap having a second coupler; and, a padded sleeve on the second strap, the padded sleeve being slidable along the second strap; and, a seat having a seat back, the seat back having a back side, a top, and a front side, and the seat back having a first complementary coupler complementary to the first coupler on the distal end of the first strap and located proximal to the top of the seat back, and the seat back having a second complementary coupler complementary to the second coupler on the distal end of the second strap and located proximal to the top of the seat back. 11. An apparatus for supporting a person's head while the person is seated, the apparatus comprising: a sling having a first end, a second end, and a length between the first end and the second end, the length of the sling being adjustable; the first end of the sling having a first coupler; the second end of the sling having a second coupler; and, 

a seat having a seat back, the seat back having a back side, a top, and a front side, and the seat back having a first complementary coupler complementary to the first coupler on the first end of the sling and located proximal to the top of the seat back, and the seat back having a second complementary coupler complementary to the second coupler second end of the sling and located proximal to the top of the seat back. 12. The apparatus of Claim 11, further comprising; a pad on the sling, the pad being slidable along the length of the sling. 13. The apparatus of Claim 11, wherein; the first coupler on the first end of the sling and the first complementary coupler on the seat are magnetically attracted to each other; and, the second coupler on the second end of the sling and the second complementary coupler on the seat are magnetically attracted to each other. 14. The apparatus of Claim 11, wherein; the first coupler and the first complementary coupler are complementary portions of a first snapping coupler, and the second coupler and the second complementary coupler are complementary portions of a second snapping coupler.
